LAGOS – The Nigerian equities market on Thursday advanced 0.07 per cent on the back of buying interests in some high capitalised stocks to reverse the negative run. The All Share Index (ASI) gained 21.13 basis points, representing a growth of 0.07 per cent to close at 29,919.44 points while market capitalisation gained N8 billion to close at N11.244 trillion. The upturn was impacted by gains recorded in medium and large capitalised stocks, amongst which are; Seplat Petroleum Development Company, Forte Oil, Dangote Flour Mills, Nigerian Breweries and Stanbic IBTC Holdings. Analysts at Afrinvest Limited noted that: “Following yesterday’s positive performance, we do not rule out the possibility of profit taking in today’s trading session amidst corporate earnings releases.” Besides, analysts at APT Securities and Funds Limited encouraged investors to position for mid to long term on fundamentally justifiable stocks that have shed weight over time. The market breadth closed positive, with 19 gainers versus 17 losers. Cutix recorded the highest price gain of 10 per cent, to close at N1.87, per share. Forte Oil followed with a gain of 9.88 per cent to close at N26.70, while Dangote Flour Mills appreciated by 9.69 per cent, to close at N14.15, per share. NPF Microfinance Bank went up by 9.35 percent, to close at N1.52, while Japaul Oil & Maritime Services rose by 8.33 per cent to close at 26 kobo, per share. On the other hand,Guinness Nigeria and Julius Berger led the losers’ chart by 10 per cent, each to close at N48.60 and N22.50, respectively, while UAC of Nigeria followed with a decline of 9.35 per cent to close at N6.30, per share.